Supergravity solutions 
In this section we are going to develop the formalism needed to obtain
supergravity backgrounds for the brane-wave intersections studied in the
brane probe approach of the previous section. We will also analyze the
degrees of supersymmetry of the different solutions and  compare them
with the ones corresponding to the brane probe.



The eleven dimensional metrics of the solutions we will be dealing with are
warped generalizations of the line element written in eq. (), namely:
ds^2_11 =h_1(2dx^+dx^-+W(dx^+)^2+(dx^a)^2)+
h_2(dx^ )^2,
where we have distinguished between transverse coordinates parallel to the
brane worldvolume () and those orthogonal to it ().
The warp factors  and  are taken to depend on the external
coordinates
, whereas the profile  can depend on both sets of
coordinates. Actually, we will adopt the ansatz in which  and 
are powers of the same function . These powers are different for the M2
and M5 branes:
&&h_1=H^-23  ,
h_2=H^13  ,(M2 ),&&h_1=H^-13  ,
h_2=H^23  ,(M5 ).
Notice that the warp factors in () are exactly the same ones which
appear in the pure M2 or M5 solutions.
The four-form field  will be taken as a sum of a wave contribution

and a brane contribution .
We shall assume that  is given by the same expression as in eq.
(), :
F_wave =dx^+ ,
where  is defined in eq. ().
For an M2-brane extended along , the contribution to the
four-form field strength will be given by the standard "electric" ansatz:
F_M2 =dx^+ dx^- dx^a dH^-1 ,
while for the M5-brane we will adopt the following magnetic ansatz:
F_M5 = ^* dH.
In eq. ()  denotes the Hodge dual with respect to
the external coordinates  with the Euclidean metric.
The total field strength  must satisfy the Bianchi identity, , and
the field equation:
d ^*F=12 FF,
where  denotes the Hodge dual for the eleven dimensional metric
(). These equations for  are enough to fix the precise
dependence of  on the external coordinates . Indeed, we
will show that, in general,  will only depend on some subset of
the 's and it will be a harmonic function on the other
external coordinates. The independence of  on some
's means that the brane is smeared along those directions
and, thus, our M-branes are delocalised objects in transverse space. This
remark will be relevant when comparing the number of supersymmetries of the
supergravity solutions with those obtained within the brane probe approach.

The metric and gauge field must also satisfy Einstein's equations, which,
written in flat coordinates, read:
